larly advanced self-critical tendencies--their "Jewish self-hatred.? Provocative and elegantly argued, On the Origins of Jewish Self-Hatred challenges widely held notions about the history and meaning of this idea, and explains why its history is so badly misrepresented today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAntisemitismxPsychological aspects. 0aSelf-hate (Psychology). 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAdage.  aAdolf Loos.  aAfrikan Spir.  aAlfred Kerr.  aAnti-Zionism.  aAnti-imperialism.  aAnti-nationalism.  aAntisemitism (authors).  aAntisemitism.  aAnxiety of influence.  aBildung.  aBildungsroman.  aBoris Groys.  aBuddenbrooks.  aConsciousness.  aCounter-revolutionary.  aCultural pessimism.  aDefamation.  aDeportation.  aEdmund Husserl.  aErudition.  aErving Goffman.  aFeuilleton.  aFranz Kafka.  aFranz Werfel.  aFritz Haarmann.  aGerman Forest.  aGerman nationalism.  aGermans.  aGershom Scholem.  aGustav Wyneken.  aHans Gross.  aHans Mayer.  aHatred.  aHeinrich Heine.  aHeinrich von Kleist.  aHighbrow.  aHis Family.  aHouston Stewart Chamberlain.  aHugo Bettauer.  aHumiliation.  aHypocrisy.  aJacques Derrida.  aJakob Wassermann.  aJewish assimilation.  aJewish guilt.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aKarl Kraus (writer).  aKurt Tucholsky.  aLecture.  aLessing.  aLudwig Klages.  aLudwig Wittgenstein.  aMartin Buber.  aModern Paganism.  aModernity.  aMoses Mendelssohn.  aNarrative.  aNovelist.  aOedipus complex.  aOn the Jewish Question.  aOppression.  aOswald Spengler.  aOtto Gross.  aOtto Weininger.  aPacifism.  aPaul Heyse.  aPersecution.  aPessimism.  aPhilosophy.  aPity.  aPogrom.  aPolemic.  aPrejudice.  aProstitution.  aPsychoanalysis.  aRainer Maria Rilke.  aRidicul